result.execSummary:
The defendant David M. Simplot was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. David M. Simplot is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • David M. Simplot was found guilty of Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

DA Gerald Fox appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Poss.  Plead no contest to Count 2.  Victim notification complied with.  Restitution worksheet on file applies to the dismissed count only.   Court recited the charge and possible penalties of the charge he plead to.  Defendant understood.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant.  Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea. Found guilty of Disorderly Conduct, contrary to 947.01(1).  Joint recommendation for:  $25, plus costs.  Court ordered the same.  $484.50 total fine and costs.    Court advised defendant of the DNA submission requirement.   Pay @ $100/mo starting 7/1.  Failure to pay any part of the fine or court costs in full by the due date will result in 1 day jail for each $25 left unpaid.
